    color: '#0891b2',
    tag: 'DECLARATIVE',
    intro: 'GitOps only works because the manifests are declarative: they describe the end state you want — "three replicas of this image, exposed on this port" — not the steps to achieve it. Kubernetes YAML is the canonical example, but the same applies to Helm charts and Kustomize overlays that render down to YAML. Declarative state is what makes reconciliation possible: a machine can compare "what Git says" to "what the cluster has" and compute the difference, because both are just data. Imperative scripts ("run this, then that") cannot be diffed or self-healed — declarative manifests can.',
    deepDive: 'The declarative model is the same idea Kubernetes and Terraform are built on, and GitOps extends it to the whole delivery flow. A manifest must be complete and idempotent: applying it twice yields the same result, and it fully specifies intent so nothing depends on hidden cluster state or manual prior steps. This is why GitOps strongly favors immutable image tags (a digest or version, never :latest) — :latest makes the desired state ambiguous, so two reconciliations could produce different running code with no Git change to explain it. Manifests should also avoid embedding environment-specific values inline; that variation belongs in Kustomize overlays or Helm values so the base stays reusable. The payoff: because intent is fully captured as data in Git, you can recreate the entire environment from scratch by pointing an operator at the repo.',
