    tag: 'RECONCILE',
    intro: 'Reconciliation is the heartbeat of GitOps. On a loop — every few minutes, or instantly via a Git webhook — the operator fetches the desired state from Git, reads the live state from the cluster, computes the difference, and applies whatever is needed to close the gap. This is the exact same control-loop pattern Kubernetes controllers use internally, lifted up to the level of "the whole application versus the whole repo." A sync is just one turn of that loop. Because it runs continuously, the cluster is not deployed once and left to drift; it is perpetually nudged back toward what Git says.',
    deepDive: 'A sync has phases worth understanding. First the operator renders the manifests (running Kustomize or Helm if needed) to produce the final desired YAML. Then it diffs that against live objects and shows the result as OutOfSync with a precise per-resource diff. Applying can be automated (the operator syncs the moment Git changes) or manual (a human clicks sync / runs argocd app sync as a gate before prod). Sync waves and hooks order the apply — CRDs and namespaces before the workloads that depend on them, with pre/post-sync hooks for migrations. Pruning is the sharp edge: when you delete a manifest from Git, prune tells the operator to delete the corresponding live object — powerful and occasionally dangerous, which is why it is often gated. The reconciliation loop is also what makes GitOps recover from disasters: point a fresh cluster at the repo and it rebuilds itself, sync by sync.',
