    intro: 'Drift is when the live cluster diverges from what Git says — almost always because someone ran kubectl edit during an incident, an autoscaler changed a replica count, or another controller mutated a resource. Plain CI/CD deploys are blind to this: they only act when you trigger them, so an out-of-band change sits unnoticed until the next deploy clobbers or preserves it unpredictably. GitOps continuously detects drift as part of every reconciliation and, with self-heal enabled, automatically reverts the live object back to the Git-declared state — making Git not just the deploy source but the enforced truth.',
    deepDive: 'Self-healing is the property that elevates GitOps from "deploy from Git" to "Git is law." With selfHeal enabled, a manual kubectl scale checkout --replicas=10 is detected within the reconciliation interval and reverted to the value in Git — the cluster simply will not stay changed unless Git changes. This is a powerful guardrail (no more mystery config that exists only in someone\'s shell history) but it has sharp edges: an emergency manual fix gets undone unless you also commit it, so the correct incident response under GitOps is "commit the fix to Git," not "patch the cluster." Some fields legitimately change outside Git (HPA-managed replicas, controller-injected annotations); those are excluded with ignoreDifferences so the operator does not fight other controllers in an endless sync loop. Drift detection without self-heal is also valid — surface the divergence and alert, but let humans decide — which many teams prefer for production until they trust the automation.',
