    tag: 'STRUCTURE',
    intro: 'How you lay out your GitOps repositories shapes everything downstream — review scope, blast radius, and how easy promotion is. The first decision is the app/config split: keep application source code and deployment config in separate repositories so a config change (and the operator that watches it) is cleanly decoupled from a code change and its CI. The second is how many config repos and how to arrange environments inside them. There is no single right answer, but there are well-worn patterns and clear anti-patterns.',
    deepDive: 'A monorepo config repository (all apps and environments in one repo) gives one place to review, easy cross-cutting changes, and a single source of truth — but coarse access control and a larger blast radius. Multiple config repos (per team or per app) give tight ownership and isolation at the cost of cross-app changes spanning several PRs. For environments, directory-per-environment inside the repo is the dominant, recommended pattern because every environment\'s full state is visible and promotion is a clear file diff; branch-per-environment is discouraged because it hides inter-environment drift. The key anti-pattern to avoid is mixing app code and config in the same repo and branch, which couples CI rebuilds to config-only changes and muddies the GitOps handoff. Whatever the layout, branch protection and CODEOWNERS on the config repo turn structure into a real production access-control boundary.',
    example: {
      scenario: 'A platform team must choose a layout that gives clear ownership and visible environment promotion.',
      action: 'They split app code from config, use one config repo with directory-per-environment, and apply CODEOWNERS for review scope.',
      code: '# Separate repos:\n#   acme/checkout         (app code + CI -> builds image)\n#   acme/config-repo      (deployment config, watched by operator)\n\n# config-repo: directory-per-environment\n# apps/\n#   checkout/{base, overlays/staging, overlays/prod}\n#   payments/{base, overlays/staging, overlays/prod}\n# platform/   (shared: ingress, monitoring, rbac)\n\n# CODEOWNERS scopes review:\n#   apps/checkout/  @checkout-team\n#   platform/       @platform-team',
    },
    responsibilities: [
      'Separate application code from deployment config',
      'Choose mono- vs multi-repo by ownership and blast radius',
      'Prefer directory-per-environment over branch-per-environment',
      'Avoid coupling CI rebuilds to config-only changes',
      'Use branch protection and CODEOWNERS as access control',
    ],
    docUrl: 'https://argo-cd.readthedocs.io/en/stable/user-guide/best_practices/',
    docLabel: 'Argo CD repo best practices',
